**Charles II of England, Scotland, and Ireland: The Merry Monarch and the Restoration of the Crown**

---

### **Early Life and Exile: A Prince in Turmoil**

Charles II, born on 29 May 1630 at [St James's Palace](/St_James%27s_Palace) in London, was the eldest surviving son of [Charles I of England, Scotland, and Ireland](/Charles_I_of_England,_Scotland_and_Ireland) and [Henrietta Maria of France](/Henrietta_Maria_of_France), sister of [Louis XIII of France](/Louis_XIII). His birth was met with grandeur, and he was baptised in the [Chapel Royal](/Chapel_Royal) by [William Laud](/William_Laud), the future [Archbishop of Canterbury](/Archbishop_of_Canterbury). His godparents included his maternal uncle, Louis XIII, and his grandmother, [Marie de' Medici](/Marie_de%27_Medici), both prominent figures in the French Catholic court. From birth, Charles was bestowed with the titles [Duke of Cornwall](/Duke_of_Cornwall) and [Duke of Rothesay](/Duke_of_Rothesay), and by the age of eight, he was designated [Prince of Wales](/Prince_of_Wales), though he was never formally invested with the title.

The political landscape of Charles's childhood was dominated by the escalating tensions between his father, Charles I, and the [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England). These tensions culminated in the outbreak of the [First English Civil War](/First_English_Civil_War) in 1642. Charles, along with his younger brother [James](/James_II_of_England), witnessed the [Battle of Edgehill](/Battle_of_Edgehill) in October 1642, an early engagement in the conflict. As the war progressed, the royalist cause faltered, and by 1646, Charles was forced into exile to avoid capture by [Parliamentarian](/Roundhead) forces. His journey took him from [Falmouth](/Falmouth,_Cornwall) to the [Isles of Scilly](/Isles_of_Scilly), then to [Jersey](/Jersey), and finally to France, where his mother had already sought refuge under the protection of the young [Louis XIV](/Louis_XIV).

Charles's exile was marked by political maneuvering and personal hardship. He spent time in [The Hague](/The_Hague), where his sister [Mary, Princess Royal](/Mary,_Princess_Royal_and_Princess_of_Orange), and her husband, [William II, Prince of Orange](/William_II,_Prince_of_Orange), offered support to the royalist cause. However, the royalist efforts were ultimately unsuccessful, and Charles I was executed on 30 January 1649. Following his father's death, the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) proclaimed Charles II as king on 5 February 1649. Despite this recognition, England entered a period known as the [English Interregnum](/English_Interregnum), during which the country was governed as a republic under the leadership of [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell).

Charles's attempts to reclaim his throne were met with resistance. His alliance with the Scots led to the [Anglo-Scottish War](/Anglo-Scottish_war_(1650%E2%80%931652)) and culminated in his defeat at the [Battle of Worcester](/Battle_of_Worcester) on 3 September 1651. Charles's escape from Worcester, during which he famously hid in an oak tree at [Boscobel House](/Boscobel_House), became the stuff of legend. He eventually fled to [Normandy](/Normandy), where he spent the next nine years in exile, moving between France, the [Dutch Republic](/Dutch_Republic), and the [Spanish Netherlands](/Spanish_Netherlands).

