### **Restoration and Reign: The Return of the Merry Monarch**

The death of Oliver Cromwell in 1658 and the subsequent political instability in England created an opportunity for Charles's restoration. [George Monck](/George_Monck), a key military figure, played a crucial role in facilitating Charles's return. Monck's actions led to the dissolution of the [Rump Parliament](/Rump_Parliament) and the recall of the [Long Parliament](/Long_Parliament), which had been excluded during [Pride's Purge](/Pride%27s_Purge). The resulting [Convention Parliament](/Convention_Parliament_(1660)) welcomed Charles's [Declaration of Breda](/Declaration_of_Breda), in which he promised leniency, religious tolerance, and cooperation with Parliament.

Charles landed at [Dover](/Dover) on 25 May 1660 and entered London on 29 May, his 30th birthday, to widespread public acclaim. His restoration marked the end of the English Interregnum and the beginning of the [Stuart Restoration](/Stuart_Restoration). Charles's return was celebrated with grandeur, and he was crowned at [Westminster Abbey](/Westminster_Abbey) on 23 April 1661.

Despite his promises of religious tolerance, Charles's reign was marked by religious and political tensions. The [Clarendon Code](/Clarendon_Code), a series of laws passed by the [Cavalier Parliament](/Cavalier_Parliament), aimed to shore up the position of the [Church of England](/Church_of_England) and suppress [non-conformity](/Nonconformist_(Protestantism)). These laws included the [Corporation Act 1661](/Corporation_Act_1661), the [Act of Uniformity 1662](/Act_of_Uniformity_1662), the [Conventicle Act 1664](/Conventicle_Act_1664), and the [Five Mile Act 1665](/Five_Mile_Act_1665).

Charles's foreign policy was equally complex. His marriage to [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza) in 1662 brought significant benefits to England, including the port of [Tangier](/Portuguese_Tangier) and the [Seven Islands of Bombay](/Seven_Islands_of_Bombay). However, his alliance with [Louis XIV of France](/Louis_XIV) through the [Treaty of Dover](/Treaty_of_Dover) in 1670 raised concerns about his Catholic sympathies. Charles's secret promise to convert to Catholicism at an unspecified future date further fueled these suspicions.

